1-6353DCB36C1B"><gtr:id>6535A2DD-619C-4D44-A8B1-6353DCB36C1B</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Barry</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Hugo</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Hirst</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>CO_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=G0400849"><gtr:id>175636BD-3924-49DB-B19B-1B7BD68512FC</gtr:id><gtr:title>Group A streptococcal fimbriae - novel surface structures interacting with human tonsil</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>G0400849</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>Streptococcus pyogenes (also called the Group A Streptococcus or GAS) is an important bacterial pathogen of humans. This pathogen causes a wide variety of human infections with varying degrees of severity, including bacterial pharyngitis and tonsillitis (?strep throat?). While sporadic infections may be successfully treated with conventional antibiotics, a number of patients, both children and adults, suffer frequently recurring bouts of infection, such that surgical removal of the tonsils becomes the clinical treatment of choice. This is a major cost to the NHS and other health services throughout the world. Exploiting recently available new information (e.g. from genome sequencing), this project will look at the mechanisms whereby S. pyogenes interacts with human tonsils. This will provide new insight into how this bacterial pathogen binds to human tonsils and the response of the tonsils. Such insight may provide the basis of new, non-surgical, treatments for tonsillitis. Results of the research will be presented at national and international conferences. These are covered by the press and other media. In addition Newcastle University Public elations Office is well-versed with disseminating findings of interest to the general public</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>Streptococcus pyogenes (= the Group A streptococci) is one of the most versatile bacterial pathogens in both the variety and the severity of diseases it can cause in humans. These range from mild self-limiting infections of the pharynx or skin to some of the most devastating bacterial infections known. A wide variety of cell-surface and released products that are likely to contribute to this pathogenic versatility have been described, but analysis of recently completed genome sequences suggest strongly that others await discovery. Our understanding of the roles of S.pyogenes products in virulence is based to a lage extent on studies that have employed a varirty of in vitro and in vivo models, but in many cases the extent to which these mimic the natural host can be questioned. 

This project proposal stems from preliminary studies that have combined the complementary expertise of our laboratories and (i) established a human tonsil ex vivo tissue model to study S. pyogenes ? host epithelial interactions that are directly relevant to human disease; (ii) discovered that S.pyogenes can express previously undescribed polymeric cell-surface fimbriae, which are structurally quite distinct cell surface M protein fibrils (though these have sometimes been described inaccurately as ?fimbriae?); and (iii) demonstrated that a fimbrial associated protein (tentatively termed Fap-1) is required for S.pyogenes adhesion to intact human tonsil epithelium, but not to cultured Hep-2 cells, emphasising the limitations of readily available and widely used models. Our specific objectives are to (a) identify and characterise genes and gene products involved in the biogenesis of S. pyogenes fimbriae and explore their roles in fimbrial biogenesis; (b) explore the extent of structural variation between the fimbriae expressed by distinct strains and why some strains appear, from preliminary studies, to lack fimbriae (at least when grown in vitro), while others are very sparsely fimbriated, and others are highly fimbriated; (c) explore the relative importance/contributions of fimbrial-associated and nonfimbrial associated S. pyogenes surface proteins in interactions with human tonsil tissue and other cellular models and (d) explore host cell responses to S.pyogenes adhesion, including the reported possibility that human tonsil epithelial cells may provide a temporary intracellular nich that could explain treatment failures despite the continued sensitivity of S.pyogenes to penicilins.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-06-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2005-07-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>397823</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>0C0E62D2-5F1D-42F8-9909-0333E5264AA8</gtr:id><gtr:title>Roles of minor pilin subunits Spy0125 and Spy0130 in the serotype M1 Streptococcus pyogenes strain SF370.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Journal of bacteriology</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/f5135116adf9c208d092e51f66752825"><gtr:id>f5135116adf9c208d092e51f66752825</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Smith WD</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2010-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>0021-9193</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>TDn3XH7Z3zT</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>42DB3F99-36E7-427D-8228-0E78520CE2A8</gtr:id><gtr:title>Crystal structure of Streptococcus pyogenes sortase A: implications for sortase mechanism.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>The Journal of biological chemistry</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/a5f74241b7fae6a568fcd2dbcea1f2f9"><gtr:id>a5f74241b7fae6a568fcd2dbcea1f2f9</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Race PR</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2009-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>0021-9258</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>E94356C3BAA</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>FBD63D8B-8080-4E09-BA5E-26E03F9EBE8F</gtr:id><gtr:title>A highly unusual thioester bond in a pilus adhesin is required for efficient host cell interaction.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>The Journal of biological chemistr